Engineering Failure Analysis & Resolutions

This document records critical failures discovered during development, their root causes, and the engineering fixes implemented to improve reliability, portability, and scalability.

The goal of documenting these issues is to ensure the system is robust, production-ready, and resilient under real-world conditions.

1. Windows Build Failure Before Maven Starts

Affected File

mvnw.cmd:92
When It Breaks

Running mvnw.cmd in certain Windows environments.

Observed Error
Cannot index into a null array
Root Cause

The Maven wrapper script attempts to access:

(Get-Item $MAVEN_M2_PATH).Target[0]

If Target is null, PowerShell throws an exception, causing the wrapper to terminate before Maven is executed.

Solution

Added null-safe handling before accessing the target index.

Key improvements:

Verify that Target exists

Verify that Target contains elements

Provide a fallback path when no symlink is present

Fallback path used:

$MAVEN_M2_PATH/wrapper/dists
Why This Works

Removes reliance on fragile symlink/junction assumptions, making the Maven wrapper compatible across more Windows configurations.

2. Build Portability Risk Due to Java 25 Requirement

Affected File

pom.xml:30
When It Breaks

Compilation fails when developers or CI systems run:

Java 17

Java 21 (common LTS environments)

Root Cause

The project originally targeted:

<java.version>25</java.version>

Older JDK versions cannot compile or run Java 25 bytecode.

Solution

Changed the project to use Java 21 (LTS).

Additionally enforced the version using Maven Enforcer Plugin.

Example configuration:

<java.version>21</java.version>
Why This Works

Using Long Term Support (LTS) versions ensures compatibility across:

CI/CD pipelines

developer environments

production servers

3. Data Inconsistency Due to Split Transactions

Affected Files

WorkoutController.java:31
WorkoutController.java:32
WorkoutService.java:19
GoalService.java:24
When It Breaks

Scenario:

Workout save operation succeeds

Goal update operation fails due to lock/timeout

Result:

Workout stored
Goal update failed

This creates partial commits and inconsistent system state.

Root Cause

Each service method had independent transaction boundaries.

Example:

workoutService.saveWorkout();
goalService.updateGoal();

If the second call fails, the first one remains committed.

Solution

Introduced a single application-level transactional method.

Example:

@Transactional
public void saveWorkoutAndUpdateGoal(...) {
    workoutService.saveWorkout(...);
    goalService.updateGoal(...);
}
Why This Works

Ensures atomic operations:

Either all operations succeed OR all operations roll back
4. Multi-Instance Race Condition Creating Duplicate Goal Records

Affected Files

GoalService.java:45
FitnessGoal.java:11
When It Breaks

In distributed deployments with multiple application instances.

Scenario:

Instance A checks if goal exists
Instance B checks if goal exists
Both attempt to insert

Result:

Duplicate goal records created
Root Cause

synchronized blocks only protect threads within a single JVM, not across multiple application instances.

Solution

Moved concurrency control to the database layer.

Implemented:

Unique constraint on goal identifier

Retry logic on insert conflict

Example approach:

INSERT ... ON CONFLICT RETRY
Why This Works

The database acts as the single source of truth, preventing duplicates across all application instances.

5. Lock Contention Causing HTTP 500 Errors Under Load

Affected Files

FitnessRepo.java:18
GoalService.java:40
When It Breaks

During high concurrency when multiple requests attempt to update the same data.

Root Cause

Use of:

PESSIMISTIC_WRITE

Transactions wait for locks and may eventually timeout or deadlock.

Result:

JPA exception → HTTP 500 error
Solution

Implemented:

Lock timeout configuration

Retry logic with exponential backoff

Optional optimistic locking using @Version

Why This Works

Instead of failing immediately, the system retries transient conflicts, improving reliability under load.

6. Exception Handler Failure and Incorrect Error Classification

Affected File

GlobalExceptionHandler.java:21
GlobalExceptionHandler.java:27
When It Breaks

During validation errors involving ObjectError.

Root Cause

Handler attempted to cast all validation errors to:

FieldError

This caused:

ClassCastException

Additionally, generic RuntimeException mapping returned HTTP 500 even for client mistakes.

Solution

Improved error handling:

Safe handling of ObjectError

Explicit handlers for common cases

Added mappings:

IllegalArgumentException → 400
ResourceNotFoundException → 404
Generic fallback → 500
Why This Works

Prevents the exception handler from crashing and improves API error clarity.

7. Unbounded Fetch Causing Memory Risk

Affected File

WorkoutService.java:39
When It Breaks

When the workout dataset grows significantly.

Root Cause

Using:

findAll()

This loads the entire dataset into memory.

Risks:

High memory usage

GC pressure

Potential OutOfMemoryError

Solution

Implemented pagination using Spring Data Pageable.

Example:

Page<Workout> workouts = repo.findAll(pageable);
Why This Works

Pagination ensures:

bounded memory usage

predictable response times

scalable data access

8. Data Loss on Application Restart

Affected File

application.properties:2
When It Breaks

When the application restarts or crashes.

Root Cause

Using an in-memory database:

jdbc:h2:mem:

All data exists only in process memory.

Solution

Configured persistent databases for non-development environments:

PostgreSQL / MySQL

H2 retained only for development profile.

Why This Works

Data now survives:

restarts

deployments

system crashes

9. Production Security Risk from H2 Console

Affected File

application.properties:7
When It Breaks

If deployed with the same configuration used for development.

Root Cause

H2 console endpoint exposed publicly.

This introduces a database access surface.

Solution

Disabled console by default.

Enabled only for development environments.

Example:

spring.h2.console.enabled=false
Why This Works

Reduces attack surface and prevents unauthorized data access.

Conclusion

Through these fixes the system now has improvements in:

Build portability

Transactional consistency

Concurrency safety

API reliability

Memory efficiency

Data persistence

Security posture

This documentation serves as a technical record of failure-driven improvements applied during development.
